@node intro "Introduction"
Introduction :
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I once came across a command named 'reset' ; it looked good, and it
was rather small, so I was really happy with it, but then ...

As we all know resetting your Amiga can be dangerous, especially when
there is/was any disk-activity at the time of your reset. I guess we 
all experienced that many times ; disk not validated anymore, and 
sometimes loss of data.

Well, here is ShutDown. This new command will prompt you with a @{"ReqTools" link reqtools}
requester before it resets the computer, securing your data, because all 
tasks can and will be finished. A real ShutDown as on UN*X systems.

This version, v1.4 is the first one which lacks StatRAM support. I decided
to drop the support for this excellent package because everyone was using
StatRAM-3, and I dislike that version (I stick to StatRAM-2). If enough
interest is shown, I might be able to add the support for StatRAM-3 again,
so if you really want it, send @{" me " link author} a mail, OK ?

Maybe I'll add some more features, although I started coding this
Software just to try out some ReqTools-possibilities. It worked just
great, and therefor I decided to share the command with the rest of
the world ; who knows who might use it ? :-)

@endnode

@node execution "Execution"
Execution :
~~~~~~~~~~~
Executing the program really isn't hard : just double click the icon or 
type 'ShutDown' in a shell-window. From there onwards you'll be guided
through the command thanks to the excellent  @{" ReqTools " link reqtools} interface.

As I already said, for the moment no tooltypes possible, but on the other
hand I mostly use Shell, so why should I implement it ?
Anyway, if I have enough time to add the missing code (see @{" To Do " link todo}),
I might do it. Send me mail if you like to see this added.

As of version 1.4, ShutDown doesn't take any options ; all work is done
by the excellent ReqTools library. So you only need to click the icon,
or type its name in your favorite Shell-window.

Example:

 ShutDown

That's it! Simple, eh?

@endnode

@node install "Installation"
Installation :
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This is the easy part ...
Installing ShutDown isn't very tough ; you just need to copy it somewhere
in your path, and that's all there is to be done. Simple, eh ?

e.g.

 copy ShutDown C:

Will copy the ShutDown program to your C: assign, which is always in the
path, and will always give you access to the ShutDown command.

And of course, for those among you that don't have ReqTools.library 
installed in LIBS: (Shame on you !), I'd suggest to copy it to LIBS:

e.g. 
 
 copy ReqTools.library LIBS:

will do the job for you ...

Perhaps I'll add an Install-script in the future, if interest is shown.

@endnode

